= Brüning's Race against Time

Brüning's days are numbered. The only reason President Hindenburg is keeping him around is solely by the fact of his foreign policy expertise, and his claim that he's only 'one hundred meters from the finish line' from achieving a huge breakthrough in terms of securing an abolishment of reparations at Lausanne and Germany's rearmament at Geneva, an issue close to Hindenburg's heart. The only hope for Brüning's political salvation rests in those conferences. [? if not hindenburg_sacked: There is also no precedent of the President sacking a government that still enjoys a parliamentary majority. ?]

However, General Kurt von Schleicher sees Brüning as the biggest obstacle in his '<span class="tooltip-text" title="Coined by conservative elites like Schleicher and Papen, this strategy aims to control the dynamic Nazi movement and integrate it into the state by introducing the party to government. In their eyes, this would moderate the Nazis, transforming them into a constructive component of the state.">taming strategy</span>', as Brüning has refused to take serious efforts toward bringing the <span style="color: #7A3C00;">national</span> <span style="color: #3E88B3;">opposition</span> into government. The sense of urgency Schleicher has invoked onto the issue, along with his convincing of Hindenburg's State Secretary Otto Meissner and his son Oskar, has brought Hindenburg to make an early and rash decision on the matter.

