To most political observers, Carl Goerdeler, Mayor of Leipzig and the Reich Prize Commissioner, and being a fiscal conservative arguing for a wide reaching reforms of the German welfare state and finances, was the expected successor to Brüning, with his name even being floated around as the Minister-President of Prussia of a <span style="color: #000000;">Center</span>-<span style="color: #7A3C00;">**NSDAP**</span> coalition.

However, his demands for authorization of sweeping fiscal reforms is too similar to that of Brüning in Schleicher's eyes, who supports a public works solution to Germany's economic woes. Goerdeler will not be the new chancellor.

