With Goerdeler and Westarp out of the equation, Hindenburg has grasped the straw Schleicher offered and appointed a far-right Catholic Conservative, Franz von Papen, from the <span style="color: #000000;">Center Party</span>, as chancellor. Papen is relatively unknown, only whose political experience is limited to two terms in the Prussian Landtag. The two have been friends since their days in the Prussian military academy.

Papen's decision to take the chancellorship, despite [+ z_leader +]'s urging and Papen's promise not to, Hindenburg has used the same tactic on him as he used on Brüning, convincing him to accept the position. Due to Papen breaking his promise to [+ z_leader +] just after he made it, expulsion proceedings and against him are interrupted by his resignation from the <span style="color: #000000;">Center Party</span>, forever ruining his relations with the party necessary for a parliamentary majority as they strongly denounce him as the "Ephialtes of the <span style="color: #000000;">Center Party</span>".

It's unknown of the exact reasons why Schleicher would choose a man like Papen as Brüning's successor, but we can assume he was trying to secure the support of the <span style="color: #000000;">Center Party</span> and <span style="color: #7A3C00;">Nazis</span>, as he's a far-right member of the former, and that Papen would be an easy person to control.

Time will tell if the <span style="color: #7A3C00;">**NSDAP**</span> will honor its promises to Schleicher, which they'd purposefully refused to write on paper.